Quant Hub Engineering Handbook
05_ENGINEERING_STANDARDS
Document ID: QH-005Version: 1.0 DraftStatus: Draft
Engineering Philosophy
Engineering quality takes precedence over development speed. Every contribution must improve maintainability, readability, reliability, scalability, and testability.
Core Principles
- Architecture before implementation.- Explicit over implicit behaviour.- Single responsibility.- Loose coupling.- High cohesion.- Document significant decisions.- Every change must be reviewable.
Code Quality Standards
- Follow PEP 8.- Use Python type hints.- Public APIs require docstrings.- Avoid duplicated logic.- Keep business logic out of the UI.- No hard-coded configuration or secrets.
Error Handling
- Never ignore exceptions.- Log failures with context.- Use meaningful exception types.- Fail safely and predictably.
Logging
- Structured logging.- Record startup, shutdown, orders, warnings, and errors.- Never log credentials or secrets.
Documentation
Every module must document its purpose, responsibilities, dependencies, interfaces, and usage. Architectural changes require handbook updates.
Testing
Mandatory unit tests, integration tests for service boundaries, regression tests for bug fixes, and paper-trading validation before live deployment.
Security Baseline
Store secrets in environment variables, validate all external inputs, apply least privilege, and review dependencies regularly.
Code Review Checklist
- Architecture preserved- Tests included- Documentation updated- No duplicated logic- Security reviewed- Performance considered
Definition of Production Code
Production code is readable, tested, documented, monitored, configurable, secure, and maintainable.
Closing Statement
Engineering discipline is a feature of Quant Hub. These standards are mandatory for every module.